description.text:
This is the largest printing project I designed so far... we call it the ScoopLamp! It is a lamp made of only printed parts, it doesn't need any tools to assemble (if well printed) and no glue or screws (only a piece of steel wire or a cable tie to fix it on the bulb holder). 
The Lamp on the photos is printed with a 0.5mm nozzle. I used PLA silver for the segments and white ABS for the rings. One element took about 7 hours to print on my setup :)

First, make sure you have at least 500g of PLA ready... it needs loads of material ;)
Then make sure, your printer can handle at least parts that are around 180 x 115 x 90mm (will not work on makerbot in full size...) Then, heat up your Printer and start printing the hell out of it.. :) you need to print:
  • One piece of each ring (I made them out of ABS... more stable)
  • Print 9 pieces of the "003 Element9.stl" carefully... this means: place them at the right point of your printing platform to make sure it will not overlap - it is HUGE!!
  • Clean all the ooze (if some) and dirt of the parts carefully (I used a sharp blade...).
    • Assembly:
  • Take one "Element9" and snap the two rings in
  • Add other elements piece by piece untill all elements are assembled
    • Mounting:
  • Make sure you use a fluorescent or LED energy saving lamp that doesn't create too much heat to prevent any damage due to heat
  • Use a cable zip or a piece of wire to hold the upper ring tight around your bulb holder

This is a scanner target I designed in Solidworks to be used for the Handyscan Fuel3D scanner. It is designed to have a magnet installed in the bottom to allow for it to stick to metallic objects. The idea is to provide an object to aid in aligning scans of large near symmetric objects. Aligning scans for objects that do not have multiple recognizable features is very difficult with the portable scannrs. title: Prusa X-Carriage to GrooveMount Interface Plate

description.text: My Prusa X-Carriage is very flimsy because of all of the cutouts for various extruder mounting options. When I printed it from the git repo I should have turned a bunch off to make a more solid carriage, but once I glued it in I decided to live with it. Also, my extruder has a big motor and it's perched on a narrow, printed GrooveMount adapter http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:7107 . I never used the MakerGear adapter because it was cut off-center (for an original Wades). While testing out Marlin firmware at 200mm/s (see http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ejt8CVV0Yzk) I noticed a lot of vibration in my extruder. So to give the extruder a more stable platform I laser cut a big adapter plate. It has lots of contact area with the X carriage and allows me to tighten the mounting screws very firmly without flexing the carriage and causing it to bind. I'm half tempted to epoxy the plate right to the X carriage, but the improvement is quite visible just like this.

Laser cut from 3/16" (4.8mm) plywood. Insert your GrooveMount hot end into the large side of the keyhole with the wires sticking through the small side. Rotate it so the wires are on the large side and then snap the groove into the narrow side of the keyhole. If you have a CNC router I just noticed this Thing which may be more useful to you: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:11113

description.text:
so , .. i left the pot of water boiling too long, flame was low good thing , but all the water was gone and teh thing heated up to the point that the top melted (as seen in photo)-- to the rescue is 3d printing (i seriously doubt i could buy that plastic part replacement and then the wait for shipping !!)
I was able to very carefully break and manuever the melted plastic ring that i thought was stuck at the top.. it did take a lot of prying ! (with plastic lever) .. i realized, my distillation set sucks with only 500 ml boiler .. now with this I can mulitply by 4 times and have a 2 LITER boiler !!! ... (this was more the motivation to make than just for boiling water for tea/coffee()
last picture, using a recycled (golf ball) as a stopper in the center, water is boiling and steam is protruding up (though picture detail doesn't seem to capture this) - i didnt think pla would hold up, ball is abs . Distil v3 is the latest (17Dec15) -all the height is not needed, i tried tquickly reduce the amount of material to mostly what is functional, i did find that after about 5 min of boiling, the PLA becomes soft and the parts 'work themselves into the groove' ( it gets better with use) -- pla becomes soft at 60c so at 100c this is expected to happen --- on the v2 test a very low infil (about 2 or 3 ) was used -- about 30 grams at 3%, i suggest 5 or 10 infill so it doesnt collapse with longer boil times -- i hate to use ABS because th is not organic, so better to use more infil and stick with the pla, and not have the temps stay too high (keep flame low so pla does not melt too much) -- perhaps a thicker wall as well -- the real test will be 1 hr boil time to see if it holds up ..

Our project is a replica of a ship called a TIE Interceptor from "Star Wars". The ship is a sphere with cylinders on both sides. There are two wings with four pieces each, which are two triangular planes, one square plane, and one cube attaching them to the cylinders.

How We Made the Tie Interceptor We started with the plane shape. First we moved the bottom right corner to the right on the line to keep it straight. Then move the left corner slightly to the left, doing the same thing you did to the right to keep it straight. Finally, move the top right corner on the axis to the left. Once you are done, this part should look like one of the parts of the wing of the Tie Interceptor, with the right corner far out, the left corner slightly to the left, and the top part smaller than when you started with a plane. Once you tweak this piece until you like how it looks, duplicate it time to create a total of 2 of these pieces. Next, create another plane. Move the right side over to make this plane a rectangle. Move one of the rectangles to the left side of the working surface. Place it in the air so that you have enough room on top and on bottom for the parts of the wings you made first. Once you have this in position, place one wing piece on top and on bottom, making sure the longer parts are facing the same way for both of them. This will require rotating it so that this is possible. The longer, flatter side of the original wing pieces should be touching the rectangle. Once these are in place, rotate them so that they are facing the right side of the screen. About a 20 degree angle. When you rotate it, you will have to remove the wing pieces so that they are touching again. The top half should be the same as the bottom half. Once your wing looks like the Tie Interceptor wing, join the three pieces and duplicate it. Rotate it so that all wings are rotated towards each other, and all longer parts are facing the same way. There should be a wing on the right and left side of the area. Once you have this, create an ico sphere, make it to scale with the wings, and move it in between the wings, towards the back. It should be centered on the rectangle in the middle of the wings. Once you have done this and it is to scale, create a cylinder. Make it longer and skinnier, and this will go in between the sphere and wings. It should be touching both so that they connect. Once you have one, duplicate it and if your sphere is centered, the duplicated cylinder should fit perfectly on the other side of the sphere. Once you have this done, rotate the sphere so that the top faces forward. Then, dissolve the vertices by going to the second ring near the middle, and from the top line dissolving three vertices, then leaving one, and dissolving another three. Repeat this going all the way around. When everything is in place and edited, join everything so you can move your entire Tie Interceptor at once.

description.text:
My wife still uses a flip phone.  She refuses to go the way of a smartphone!  She wanted a phone clip which she could clip onto her pant or jeans pocket and let the phone hang down below her blouse or shirt thus avoiding the 'phone bulge'. 
This is my first stab at it and it could use some work.  The style of phone clip is one where you stick a button to the back of the phone and then you slide the phone, via the button onto the clip.  I used 3m double stick tape which I bought from my local Ace Hardware store to stick the button onto the phone.
When you print this, you will need to cut or dremel the supports off of the button track (see photo).  I also had to sand the button shaft a little but I think that's because I had the heat turned up too high when I printed it in PLA and so the shaft diameter spread wider than expected.
I uploaded the photos of the clip.  Please keep in mind this is the prototype and so I printed it in Blue and I scratched the clip when I took the supports out.  I have a couple revisions to make and when I do I will update the STL file/s.
I included the 123d design files so you can customize to your hearts desire!

title: MK7 Hack to Enable Filament Changes Mid-Print

description.text: The MK7 is great. But one thing never made it into the design spec: the ability to switch filaments mid-print. Switching filaments enables multi-colored prints without fusing filament first. It also ensures that if you run out of a given filament, you can load new stock mid-print. This is very helpful for long prints. The MK7's Stainless Steel Thermal Barrier Tube is not seated close enough to the Knurled Pulley, which makes it nearly impossible for a new filament to chase another into the Tube. However, raising the Tube ~3.5mm brings it close enough so that the new filament will not bend or slip off the old filament as it enters the Tube. Another benefit is that you gain an additional ~3.5mm in Z-height! Here's some video of the results http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I25pOHE91xY UPDATE: Zach posted a solid filament block for the MK7, so you should print this out and modify that instead of your purchased one. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:12147

You'll need a Dremel or other tool (see photo for reference) to carve away a small portion of the Molded Drive Block.
1) Keep the Molded Drive Block attached to the stepper but remove the Knurled Pulley to avoid damage and dust. Remove ~3.5mm in by ~5mm wide to accommodate the raised Stainless Steel Thermal Barrier Tube. (See photos for reference.)
2) Re-assemble your Stainless Steel Thermal Barrier Tube inside the Bar Mount so the end protrudes ~3.5mm above the M6 Nut.
3) There should be just enough thread left below the Bar Mount to secure the entire hot end back onto the Mounting Plate.
4) Test-fit the Molded Drive Block against the raised Stainless Steel Thermal Barrier Tube. If desired, secure the Bar Mount to the stepper with M3x18 screws and make a test extrusion. Insert a new filament after snipping off the old one (see video link above) to be certain it pushes the old filament through. 
5) Re-attach the Fan and Heatsink assembly.

title: Fin and Nose Cone Section for 1" Compressed Air Rocket

description.text:
I saw this kit in the latest MakerShed newsletter: http://makezine.com/projects/make-15/compressed-air-rocket/
Had to make one. I used this valve instead,
http://www.amazon.com/Orbit-57101-Sprinkler-System-1-Inch/dp/B00004S1V3
which is 1" versus the 3/4" valve in the kit. I figured bigger port means faster rocket (I'm not an engineer though). BTW, this launcher is pretty cool. We got over 100 yards on our first shot! The above rocket lasted two flights. The paper tube crumpled on the second impact, but the plastic survived. Click on the "full size view" of the last picture to see the entire rocket. Next project is to try and incorperate a whistle in the nose cone.

The cross sections are .028", so with a 0.4mm extruder, they print nicely with 1 perimeter and no infill. Since these are designed to slide on 1" SCH40 PVC, the inside dia. is about 1.345", but these should be able to be scaled down about 80% to 1.070" dia for 3/4" PVC. (may need to try it and tweak) There should be ~.010 -.015" clearance.  
To make the rocket, print a nose cone and a fin section. Put both on a section of pipe used as a mandrel. Wrap a piece of paper around the mandrel in between the nose and fin section. Tape up with a couple of layers of clear packing tape.
I'm sure it goes without saying, but these rockets should not be launched toward the vicinity of people houses vehicles, etc!

comments.text:
Prints fine in PLA with a 0.4mm Prusa i2, but tends to split along the fins with minor twisting.
I'd probably use ABS, and double the thickness if building another.

My attempt at modelling the Twelfth Doctor's new sonic screwdriver, introduced in the episode "Hell Bent". (Edit: because a couple of people have asked, the cover image is an actual photo of the finished object, not CG. The second image is of the CG model.)
Yes, there's an absurd number of parts to it. I separated into multiple parts for ease of painting and to try to eliminate overhangs. Although I separated the latches into each individual component, I also included a "prebuilt" version (though I don't think it looks quite as good when printed).
It's hollow most of the way through, in case you want to include electronics, and unscrews at a couple of points to facilitate that.
In addition to the 3D printed parts, you'll need five lengths of 5mm-diameter clear acrylic rods, and several short bits of 2mm-diameter brass wire to hold the latches together (unless you use the unibody versions). See the "build instructions" document for complete details.
The fit will be extremely tight when it comes off the printer, as it is intended that the parts be sanded down to get rid of the layer striations before painting them.

description.text: These tiny snowflake ornaments are about 25mm across and were generated with the Snowflake Machine. The models are optimized for printing on an Ultimaker 2 with ABS and the standard .4mm nozzle, at .1mm layer height. If you want snowflake ornaments that are already tested and ready to go, then print these. But it's much more fun to go make your own, so go do that at the Snowflake Machine! For 25mm snowflakes, set the "Target Diameter" to 25 in the "Global Size Settings". For this size you'll have to reduce to 4-5 steps and keep the thickness of the strands down by setting low values for "fat" and "organic". =====
